<td valign="top"  width='20'> 
 <img height=3 hspace=0 vspace=0 src="/vs/gfx/clear.gif" width=20 border=0></td>
<td valign="top" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"> 
 <img height=3 hspace=0 vspace=0 src="/vs/gfx/clear.gif" width=10 border=0></td>
<td width="80%" valign="top"  bgcolor='#FFFFFF'> 
 <!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 

            <BR><center><a href='http://www.decktech.net/adserver/click.php?mgr=aspcode.net&id=37'><img border='0' src='http://www.decktech.net/banner/dtauctions.gif'  ></a></center><div class='main'><div class='mainheader'><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="26e200cb5006276800a938cd72b8e6df" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></div><div class='maincontent'><font class="h1font"> Tales from the Man Room<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/vs/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/vs/main/mpage.php?member=17798'>James "boothwah" Booth</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/vs/main/mpage.php?member=17798&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 5, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Tales from the Man Room<br />
<br />
A brief bit of history on the draft variant I&#39;m going to share with you tomorrow.  Once upon a time, I was into all things Magic.  I had my power nine, a closet full of unlimited through 7th edition jank, home-made life counter wheels, decks for three different play environments, the enormous trade binder(s) and group of friends as rabid about the game as I once was.  I was part of a play group that frequently spent 2 to 3 evenings a week practicing draft, tuning type 2 decks, and generally ignoring things like personal hygiene and reasonable sleeping hours to go play in any ol&#39; type of tournament almost every weekend. <br />
<br />
Time, life, work, marriage, children, etc. all took larger portions of the time that I previously had frittered away playing cardboard wizard, and I disengaged myself from the world of eternal adolescence and super competitive organized play.  But, thanks to my ever-patient, geek nurturing, angel of a wife, I still held a weekly Saturday night draft session with my buds.<br />
<br />
We routinely had 6 to 10 guys show up to smoke cigars, drink beer, and draft magic in my converted garage, &quot;The Man Room,&quot; until 3:00 in the morning.  It was a poker game for comic-book geeks….with a three booster ante.  Sometimes we&#39;d play double elim, 2 out of 3 games with the winner taking all the cards they drafted and one from each other participants deck.  Or perhaps we&#39;d play a mini-master tourney and have the winner of each match win the loser&#39;s entire stack less one card, and rebuild decks with the new pile between rounds.  We would play a variant where you would try to draft the worst pile of cards possible and then your opponent each round would be forced to build a deck with them.  Sometimes we&#39;d get bored and light Polar Kraken&#39;s on fire.<br />
<br />
But as time and life caught up to my playgroup, some of them drifted away, got busy, and married non-angelic, geek crushing women.  Heck, one of them married a gal who made him take her last name.  <br />
<br />
So what do you do when you want to draft and there are only 3 of you sitting in the converted garage with a case of beer and a pack of swisher sweets.  Even worse, what do you do when Nate-Dogg decides to start drinking 3 hours before anyone gets there and passes out before you can open the packs?<br />
<br />
I&#39;ll get to that tomorrow.<br />
<br />
Fast forward 6 or 7 years.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ve sold my power nine.  Donated a closet full of Magic stuff to needy kids.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ve moved away from the hometown.  Still married to the ever-patient, geek nurturing, angel of a wife<br />
<br />
I still waste copious amounts of money on card games.  Especially LOTR.  I become a dAgent and ignite the local game shop playgroup from a paltry 3-4 players a week to regular, sanctioned tournaments once or twice a month.  My foster son really likes the game and even though he has to endure my play testing beatings.  Something is missing though.  Limited play for LOTR sucks.  After mastering the constructed environment for our local scene, each tourney turns into:  You gonna play elves or dwarves this time?<br />
<br />
Old game store owner chat&#39;s us up on a visit to the old home-town.  Says this Vs. thing is all the rage.  He puts a starter in my bag, as a gift, when I pick up my subscriptions that visit.  I can&#39;t believe I still buy all of my comic books from a retailer 350 miles from my house.  Of course, it&#39;s kind of cool picking them up every 4 months and getting to read a whole story arc at once…must be why trades do so well.  I digress.<br />
<br />
Fast forward 6 months<br />
<br />
After watching Spider Man 2 on DVD (kick ass!), Derek (the now 18 year old) says, &quot;Hey, we never did try that super-hero game that Jeremy gave us.  Does that have Spiderman in it?&quot;  We go and dig it out of the cardboard closet of shame, and realize that it&#39;s never been opened.  We open it.  No Spiderman.  A bunch of muties.  We resolve to learn mutie beat down after we run to the store to get Mountain Dew.<br />
<br />
While browsing through the electronics section at the local Fred Meyers, we stumble across the Vs. Web of Spiderman display.  &quot;Hey, there&#39;s a Spiderman right on the front.&quot;  $36.00 of impulse buying later, we head home with the Web Starter and a Magneto collectors tin.<br />
<br />
We head out to the new home&#39;s Man Room and play the Web starter to learn the rules 3 or  4 times.  My Spiderman totally owns until his Dopipeweed shows up.  We deem Sinister Salvo to be Ba-roken (C&#39;mon 3 damage and everyone gets range - no way.)  We lose track of who has initiative a couple of times.  Hilarity ensues.  Now having the rules down pat (not), we decide it&#39;s high time to bust out the Mutie decks.  Game 1 - &quot;Wolvie is Ba-roken. He killed almost my whole front line.&quot;  cuz we were of the mind that it was a waste to put guys without range in your back row, duh. Game 2 - &quot;Quit your tookin&#39;, that stinkin&#39; Magneto is so more broken than Wolvie.&quot;  Game 3 - &quot;So who do you think is hotter, Mystique or Kitty?&quot;<br />
<br />
We bust open the four packs that come in the tin and see ….Fantastic Four?  Doom?  WTF?  Cool - Geek factor 9.8 and rising, sir.  Well we split up the factions, him getting the Bro&#39;s (cuz he thought Mystique was hotter than Ms. Pryde) paired with Sinister Syndicate (cuz good guys vs. bad guys made sense) vs. my Spider Friends Saturday Cartoon Show guest starting the X-men.  BTW, the two foils we pulled out of the booster packs - Dopipeweed and the Amazing Spiderman.  We are crazy geeky happy about that.<br />
<br />
We run back to the store and grab some more packs.  Doom, the character!  The Thing!  Gambit!  More Kitty Pride!  Darkoth! &quot;Who the crap is Darkoth,&quot; Derek asks.  &quot;I don’t know, but we didn’t have one yet!&quot; <br />
<br />
We continue to play until around 2:00 and the angelic wife wakes up and sees the idiot gleam in our eyes and sternly warns us that our curfew has been invoked.  (She doesn&#39;t know that this caused a mad shopping spree on EBay, yet, or it would have been worse.)<br />
<br />
The next morning, I realize that this has a ton of the game play features I loved about Magic: the curve, limited resources, deck manipulation, cards serving as both/either attack or defense, relatively short games.  Plus, there were some similar mechanics that I liked from SWCCG and WARS: breakthrough and the cards being your resources.  Plus it satisfied the comic book geek in me that had pining away for a spandex clad hero card game ever since Overpower went away.<br />
<br />
Over the next few weeks, I start digesting the game a bit more, read a lot of articles, and realize that this would be a really good draft game.  And I have been so ready for a good draft game.  Nothing pushes my buttons like playing and winning a game with cards that rarely if ever make it into a constructed deck.  One problem:  My local playgroup at this time consists of Derek and myself.  <br />
<br />
Crap.  Crap Frickin&#39; Tastic.  Then it hits me.  We&#39;ll just try that draft variant that we used to use when Nate-Dogg passed on the couch, just without the pre-requisite pre-draft shaming.<br />
<br />
To be continued……<br />
<br />
